= Frequently Asked Questions for Patients

<ch:patient-faq>

This section addresses common questions from patients and caregivers, with
short answers and references to the detailed evidence in the main text.

/ *What is ME/CFS, and how is it different from “being tired”?*:
ME/CFS is a complex, multi-system disease characterized by profound fatigue
that is not relieved by rest, worsening of symptoms after physical or mental
exertion (post-exertional malaise, or PEM), unrefreshing sleep, cognitive
dysfunction, and orthostatic intolerance. Unlike ordinary tiredness, ME/CFS
fatigue does not improve with rest and is accompanied by measurable biological
abnormalities. See Chapter @ch:introduction for definitions and
Chapter @ch:core-symptoms for symptom details.

/ *What is PEM and why is it important?*:
Post-exertional malaise (PEM) is the hallmark feature of ME/CFS: a
disproportionate worsening of symptoms following physical, cognitive, or
emotional exertion, typically delayed by 12–72 hours and lasting days to weeks.
PEM distinguishes ME/CFS from other fatigue conditions. Two-day
cardiopulmonary exercise testing has objectively demonstrated that ME/CFS
patients show significant declines in exercise capacity on the second
day @keller2024cpet, while healthy controls do not.
See Section @sec:pem for the full evidence.

/ *Is ME/CFS psychological?*:
No. ME/CFS is a biological disease with documented abnormalities in energy
metabolism @wang2023wasf3, immune function @EatonFitch2019,
autonomic regulation @VanCampenEtAl2024, and brain
function @walitt2024deep. The 2015 Institute of Medicine
report @IOM2015 concluded that ME/CFS is a “serious, chronic, complex,
systemic disease” and explicitly rejected its classification as a
psychological disorder. See Chapter @ch:introduction and the Reading
Guide for the evidence hierarchy used in this document.

/ *Should I exercise?*:
Activity management (“pacing”) is the recommended approach, not graded
exercise therapy (GET). Research shows that ME/CFS patients have impaired
energy production that worsens after exertion @keller2024cpet. Pushing
through fatigue can trigger PEM and potentially cause lasting deterioration.
The goal is to stay within your “energy envelope”—the amount of activity
you can sustain without triggering PEM. See Chapter @ch:lifestyle for
pacing strategies and Section @sec:trials-exercise for the evidence
against GET.

/ *Are there effective treatments?*:
There is currently no cure for ME/CFS, and no single treatment works for
everyone. However, several approaches can improve quality of life:

    - *Pacing*: Staying within your energy limits is the most
      important management strategy (Chapter @ch:lifestyle)
    - *Symptom management*: Sleep, pain, orthostatic intolerance,
      and cognitive symptoms can each be addressed
      (Chapter @ch:symptom-management)
    - *Supplements*: CoQ10, NADH, and other mitochondrial
      supplements have RCT evidence of modest benefit
      (Chapter @ch:supplements)
    - *Medications*: Low-dose naltrexone, beta-blockers for POTS,
      and other targeted medications may help specific symptoms
      (Chapter @ch:medications-mechanisms)

Treatment should be individualized. See Chapters @ch:urgent-action-severe
and @ch:action-mild-moderate for severity-appropriate care pathways.

/ *Do supplements help?*:
Some supplements have evidence from randomized controlled trials:
CoQ10+NADH showed significant improvement in fatigue and quality of life in a
207-patient RCT @CastroMarrero2021fatigue; D-ribose showed improvement in
energy and well-being @Teitelbaum2006ribose. Other supplements
(magnesium, B vitamins, vitamin D) address common deficiencies but have less
ME/CFS-specific trial data. See Chapter @ch:supplements for dosing,
evidence levels, and safety considerations.

/ *What causes ME/CFS?*:
The exact cause is unknown, but evidence points to a multi-system dysfunction
involving impaired energy metabolism, immune dysregulation, and autonomic
nervous system abnormalities (the “core triad”;
Chapter @ch:integrative-models). Most cases begin after an infection,
and ongoing research investigates viral persistence, autoimmune mechanisms,
and metabolic disruption as contributing factors. Multiple biological
subgroups likely exist (Chapter @ch:disease-course).

/ *Can ME/CFS get better?*:
Recovery rates vary widely across studies, from 5% to 22% depending on
definitions and populations studied. Children and adolescents generally have
better prognosis than adults. Improvement (without full recovery) is more
common. Early diagnosis and aggressive pacing appear to improve outcomes.
See the prognosis and disease progression sections in
Chapter @ch:disease-course.

/ *How is ME/CFS diagnosed?*:
There is no single diagnostic test. Diagnosis is based on clinical criteria
requiring: (1) substantial reduction in activity lasting $gt.eq$6 months,
(2) post-exertional malaise, (3) unrefreshing sleep, plus either cognitive
impairment or orthostatic intolerance @IOM2015. Other conditions must
be excluded through standard medical workup. See
Chapter @ch:diagnostic-criteria for the major diagnostic frameworks
(Fukuda, Canadian Consensus, ICC, IOM).

/ *What should I tell my doctor?*:
Many physicians are unfamiliar with ME/CFS. Key points to communicate:

    - Describe PEM specifically: what triggers it, how long it lasts,
      and how it differs from normal fatigue
    - Request basic workup to exclude other conditions (thyroid, anemia,
      autoimmune, sleep disorders)
    - Reference the 2015 IOM diagnostic criteria @IOM2015
    - Ask about specialist referral if your GP is unfamiliar with ME/CFS

See Appendix @app:diagnostic-tools for assessment instruments and
Appendix @app:resources for specialist directories.

/ *Is ME/CFS the same as Long COVID?*:
ME/CFS and Long COVID overlap substantially: approximately 50% of Long COVID
patients meet ME/CFS diagnostic criteria. Both conditions share features
including PEM, cognitive dysfunction, and autonomic symptoms. The
pathophysiology chapters (Part II) cover mechanisms common to both conditions.
See Chapter @ch:translational-findings for cross-disease comparisons.

/ *Are there any promising treatments being researched?*:
Several approaches are in active clinical trials:

    - *Daratumumab*: An anti-CD38 antibody targeting autoimmune
      mechanisms showed 60% response in a pilot study @Fluge2025daratumumab
    - *Low-dose naltrexone*: Multiple studies underway
    - *Fecal microbiota transplant*: Large RCTs in progress
    - *BC007*: DNA aptamer neutralizing GPCR
      autoantibodies @Hohberger2021bc007

See Chapter @ch:emerging-therapies for full coverage and
Chapter @ch:clinical-trials for trial details.

